    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Ockham Park Ripley Surrey Sunday. 13th Decr</p>
      <p>My Dear Mrs. Barwell.</p>
      <p>I must take advantage of your kind offers of counsel &amp; assistance, to consult you now about my plans for the children; and in doing so I shall put aside my Secretiveness, &amp; speak quite openly.--</p>
      <p>I do not feel that by any means the attention in many ways (each small &amp; comparatively</p>
      <p>unimportant considered singly, but of moment in the mass) is given to them, especially to Byron, that they now require; and I feel it absolutely necessary that I should have assistance, &amp; that speedily.--</p>
      <p>I have been thinking much on my own qualities as a Mama or Guardian of children, &amp; I have come decisively to this conclusion: I am admirable as an organizer, director of others, superintendant. But practically in details, the less I have habitually to do with children the better both for them &amp; me.</p>
      <p>When my sisters are with me, I see far more of the children &amp; am of much greater use to them than when we are alone;-- because then there is some one exclusively devoted to them, under my direction &amp; superintendence. How many, many moments there are, when their presence is most irritating &amp; intolerable to me, &amp; when a third person given up to them, makes it quite a different thing.--</p>
      <p>Many circumstances conspire to make me singly, a bad educator.-- The pursuits &amp; tastes of years, &amp; in which time only confirms me more &amp;</p>
      <p>more;-- in short the strong natural bias of the intellect &amp; mind, as strongly marked in me as ever any natural creations since the world began; are such as render much detailed attention to children for a continuance, absolutely intolerable.-- Add to this, my total deficiency in all natural love of children, in what you would call Philo-Pragmitiveness, and an exceedingly delicate &amp; irritable nervous system which sometimes makes the very sound of their voices a source of almost uncontrollable</p>
      <p>irritability; and you will not wonder that I begin to feel them occasionally (to speak plainly but truly), a real nuisance. And this feeling, both in strength &amp; frequency, increases so much, that I feel it must not be allowed to go on, both on their account &amp; my own; &amp; I must take such measures as will materially diminish, if not wholly obviate, the causes of it.-- The last month has engendered feelings of annoyance, &amp; almost disgust, about children in general,</p>
      <p>which must result from my having been very much brought into a sort of contact with them that is most palpably against the grain. I speak strongly &amp; broadly, but I believe I speak truly; and I do not consider people to blame for their strong natural biases &amp; impulses. They are only to blame, if possessing Causality and Conscientiousness, they do not take some measures for regulating the former, &amp; endeavouring so to arrange circumstances as that all</p>
      <p>things shall fit, and any peculiarities be made of value instead of being allowed to interfere with what Nature points out as Duty.--</p>
      <p>I believe I am well fitted to educate, with proper aids. But it must be as the chief, the General; &amp; above all my sadly susceptible and irritable nerves must not be tried beyond the point where my Mind can govern their manifestations.--</p>
      <p>Now on all this I consult you, &amp; I have endeavoured to give you every datum.</p>
      <p>Of course to obtain some suitable assistant, who will act well practically in details, under me; or at times under Miss King, is the obvious desideratum.</p>
      <p>But how to obtain this?-- I end my letter with this Problem, I fear not of easy solution.--</p>
      <p>We returned here on Friday.</p>
      <p>Yours very sincerely A. A. Lovelace</p>
